1 What is a Request Object?

The Request Object (req) in Express.js represents the HTTP request sent by the client (browser or frontend) to the server.

It contains all information about the request such as:

Body data

URL parameters

Query parameters

Headers

Method (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE)

URL

Example:

app.get("/user", (req, res) => {
   console.log(req);
});


req holds all client request information.

2 What is the use of body data? When do we use it?

req.body is used to receive data sent from the client inside the request body.

It is mostly used in:

Form submissions

Login/Register APIs

Creating new data

Example:

app.post("/register", (req, res) => {
   const name = req.body.name;
   const email = req.body.email;
});

Example request body:

{
 "name":"Prem",
 "email":"prem@gmail.com"
}

 Used when sending large or structured data from frontend to backend.

3 What is the use of headers data? When do we use it?

req.headers is used to read request header information sent by the client.

Common uses:

Authentication tokens (JWT)

Content type

Browser information

Example:

app.get("/profile", (req, res) => {
   const token = req.headers.authorization;
});

Example header:

Authorization: Bearer jwt_token_here

 Used for security, authentication, and request metadata.

4 What is the use of params data? When do we use it?

req.params is used to get values from the URL path.

Example:

app.get("/user/:id", (req, res) => {
   const userId = req.params.id;
});

URL:

/user/101

Output:

101

 Used when accessing specific resources like user ID, product ID, etc.

5 What is the use of query data? When do we use it?

req.query is used to read query parameters from the URL.

Example:

app.get("/search", (req, res) => {
   const keyword = req.query.keyword;
});

URL:

/search?keyword=react

Output:

react

Used for:

Search

Filters

Pagination

6 What is Request Object and when do we use it?

The Request Object (req) is used whenever the server needs to read information from the client request.

We use it to:

Read user input (req.body)

Get URL parameters (req.params)

Read query strings (req.query)

Access headers (req.headers)

Example:

app.post("/login", (req, res) => {
   const email = req.body.email;
   const password = req.body.password;
});




